subdefinitions.definition: A syntactic marker in a question whose main verb is not another auxiliary verb or be .
examples: Do you go there often?
You seldom work on Sats, do you?

subdefinitions.definition: A syntactic marker in negations with the indicative and imperative moods.
examples: I do not go there often.
Do not listen to him.

subdefinitions.definition: A syntactic marker for emphasis with the indicative, imperative, and subjunctive moods.
examples: But I do go sometimes.
Do tell us.
Boy, did I make a mistake!
That's not true: I always do say please and thank-you.
So who did marry the Princess in the end?

subdefinitions.definition: A syntactic marker that refers back to an earlier verb and allows the speaker to avoid repeating the verb; in most dialects, not used with auxiliaries such as be , though it can be in AAVE .
examples: I play tennis; she does too.
Likes her capuccino, Mary does .
Your remarks piqued my curiosity, as it did my mom's too.
They don't think it be like it is, but it do .

subdefinitions.definition: Used to form the present progressive of verbs.

examples: If you want something done, do it yourself.
All you ever do is surf the Internet. What will you do this afternoon?
it’s not the best broom, but it will have to do ;  this will do me, thanks.
It simply will not do to have dozens of children running around such a quiet event.
The fresh air did him some good.
Our relationship isn't doing very well;  how do you do ?

subdefinitions.definition: To fare well; to thrive ; to prosper ; (of livestock) to fatten .

examples: What does Bob do ? — He's a plumber.

definitions.definition: To perform the tasks or actions associated with (something).
examples: Don't forget to do your report!
I'll just do some eggs.

definitions.definition: To travel in or through, to tour , to make a circuit of.
examples: Let’s do New York also.

definitions.definition: To treat in a certain way.
To work for or on, by way of caring for, looking after, preparing, cleaning, keeping in order, etc.
To act or behave in a certain manner; to conduct oneself.
To spend (time) in jail . ( See also do time )
examples: I did five years for armed robbery.
They really laughed when he did Clinton, with a perfect accent and a leer.

definitions.definition: To copy or emulate the actions or behaviour that is associated with the person or thing mentioned.
examples: He did a Henry VIII and got married six times.
He was planning to do a 9/11 .
definitions.label_groups: transitive , with 'a' and the name of a person, place, event, etc.

definitions.definition: To deal with for good and all; to finish up; to undo; to ruin ; to do for .

examples: He got done for speeding.
Teacher'll do you for that!

definitions.definition: To have sex with. ( See also do it )

examples: That guy just did me out of two hundred bucks!

definitions.definition: To convert into a certain form; especially, to translate .
examples: the novel has just been done into English;  I'm going to do this play into a movie

definitions.definition: To cash or to advance money for, as a bill or note.

examples: Do they do haircuts there?
Could you do me a burger with mayonnaise instead of ketchup?
I do cocaine.

definitions.definition: To exist with a purpose or for a reason.
examples: What's that car doing in our swimming pool?
definitions.label_groups: transitive , in the form be doing [somewhere]

definitions.definition: To drive a vehicle at a certain speed , especially in regard to a speed limit .
examples: He was doing 50 [miles per hour] in a school zone.
